			<h3 class="m-t-10"><i class="fa fa-cog"></i> City’s $1 billion budget reveals our collective priorities.</h3>
			<hr>
			<p>
				The City’s $1 billion budget is one of the most important piece of legislation, as it determines how much money is given to the issues that shape the City. From funding bike infrastructure and police body cameras to adding positions to make departments more effective, the scope and direction of the budget has a significant impact on how the City addresses its issues.
			</p>
			<p>
				<h4>The Process</h4>
				The process of shaping the budget includes a review of the previous year’s budget, department recommendations, feedback from a resident committee, suggestions from City Council members and City departments, which leads to a proposal by the Mayor. The Ways and Means Budget Committee then hosts a public hearing process, which takes into account resident, staff, and elected official feedback. Once the City Council adopts the budget, requests from departments for additional funds or positions are brought up as amendments for final approval. The final budget adoptions occurs after November 24th.
			</p>
			<blockquote>
				<p>“the city's budget is important because it's a monetary picture of our priorities as a city, by looking at the funding allocations, residents can learn about the city's priorities and ask questions or request changes. if you care about a particular service or program that the city does, we need to make sure its funded so it can actually happen.”</p>
				<small><cite title="Source Title">Ward 9 Council Member Alondra Cano</cite></small>
			</blockquote>
